<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-302-458  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 302 458.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 29 1989 v23 n22 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM enlists Ethernet troops in OS-2 Extended campaign.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth; Bozman, Jean S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM announces that its upcoming OS-2 Extended Edition (EE) 1.2will communicate over any Ethernet board that complies with theNetwork Driver Interface Specification, a software interfacedeveloped by 3Com Corp and Microsoft Corp. By providing thissupport, IBM acknowledges that Ethernet and Token-Ring eachaddresses a different set of user requirements.andP;  Industry analystsstate that by supporting Ethernet on OS-2 Extended, IBM stands toincrease the market for OS-2 EE by 200 percent.andP;  IBM also givesofficial recommendations to 3Com Corp, Ungermann-Bass Inc andWestern Digital Corp, which have been tested for OS-2 EE support.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products)3Com Corp. (product development)Ungermann-Bass Inc. (product development)Western Digital Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM; WDC; COMS.andO;Product:   OS-2 Extended Edition 1.2 (Operating system) (productspecifications).andO;Topic:     EthernetStandardsInterfaceCompatible SoftwareConnectivityOS-2Operating SystemsEnhancementsProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Percent of installed PC LAN nodes in 1988. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>